    2685 UPARTN Partitions a matrix based on USET Main Index Remarks: 1.The supersets formed by the union of other sets have the following definitions: 2.If IOPT<3 then SET1 or SET2, but not both, may be set to ‘COMP’ (or blank) which means that one set is the complement of the other. For example, if MAJOR=‘G’, SET1=‘A’, and SET2=‘COMP’ (or blank) then SET2 is assumed to be those degrees-of-freedom in the g-set that are not in the a-set. 3.If IOPT<3 and SET1 and SET2 are unique subsets of MAJOR but their union does not comprise all of the degrees-of-freedom in the MAJOR set, then the SET2 partition is assumed to be SET2=‘COMP’. For example, if MAJOR=‘G’, SET1=‘A’, and SET2=‘S’ then SET2 is assumed to be ‘COMP’ (See Remark 2) and not just the s-set. 4.The set names MAJOR, MAJORR, SET1, and SET2, may specify a combination of set names separated by a plus (+) or minus (-) character. The plus (+) character indicates a union and the minus (-) character an exclusion. For example, ‘a-b+m’ indicates the a-set without the b-set and then this resultant set is then unioned with the m-set. 5.USET may not be purged. 6.A may be purged, in which case UPARTN will simply return, causing the output matrices to be purged. 7.Any or all output data block(s) may be purged. 8.If IOPT<3, UPARTN internally constructs a single partitioning vector based on MAJOR and SET1 and partitions either or both the rows and columns with this same partitioning vector. For IOPT=0 this is called a symmetric partition. Whereas IOPT=3 internally constructs two partitioning vectors— the first is based on MAJOR and SET1 and the second is based on MAJORR and SET2. In other words, the columns are partitioned according to MAJOR and SET1 and the rows are partitioned according to MAJORR and SET2. This is called an asymmetric partition. For IOPT=3 UPARTN performs a similar partition as the PARTN module when the CP and RP partitioning vectors are of different sizes and/or content. See Example 4.sets mr sb sgm o q r c b e saktadffennegpsupersets l lmmp s ks jjs
